thing that touches them. The remedy for this ex|qui&s;ite
and painful &s;en&s;ibility is commonly &s;ought
from fermented, perhaps from di&s;tilled, liquors,
which render many lives wretched, that would
otherwi&s;e have been only ridiculous. The tender ner|ves,
and low &s;pirits of &s;uch poor creatures, would
be much relieved by the u&s;e of Tar-water, which
